// Perfect ğŸ‘ Letâ€™s visualize step by step with memory diagrams so the difference is crystal clear.



// 1ï¸âƒ£ Integer Array (int arr[5])
// cpp
// Copy
// Edit
// int arr[5] = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
// ğŸ”¹ Memory layout (assume int = 4 bytes):

// yaml
// Copy
// Edit
// Address    Value
// 1000       1
// 1004       2
// 1008       3
// 1012       4
// 1016       5
// â¡ï¸ Just numbers, no special symbol needed.









// 2ï¸âƒ£ Character Array (without '\0')
// cpp
// Copy
// Edit
// char letters[5] = {'H', 'e', 'l', 'l', 'o'};
// ğŸ”¹ Memory layout (assume char = 1 byte):

// yaml
// Copy
// Edit
// Address    Value
// 2000       H
// 2001       e
// 2002       l
// 2003       l
// 2004       o
// â¡ï¸ This is just an array of characters.
// â¡ï¸ If you print cout << letters; â†’ âŒ undefined behavior (because no '\0' is found to stop).








// 3ï¸âƒ£ Character Array as a String (with '\0')
// cpp
// Copy
// Edit
// char name[] = "Hello";
// Compiler stores this as:

// arduino
// Copy
// Edit
// {'H','e','l','l','o','\0'}
// ğŸ”¹ Memory layout:

// yaml
// Copy
// Edit
// Address    Value
// 3000       H
// 3001       e
// 3002       l
// 3003       l
// 3004       o
// 3005       \0   (null terminator)
// â¡ï¸ This is a C-style string.
// â¡ï¸ If you print cout << name; â†’ âœ… it will print Hello until '\0' is found.






// 4ï¸âƒ£ C++ String (std::string)
// cpp
// Copy
// Edit
// string s = "Hello";
// Internally:

// std::string is a class, not just raw memory.

// It stores characters in dynamic memory (heap), and also stores:

// length of string,

// capacity,

// pointer to char data.

// ğŸ”¹ Simplified view:

// yaml
// Copy
// Edit
// Stack (object s)
// --------------------------------
// s: { length = 5, capacity = 15, ptr â†’ 4000 }

// Heap (dynamic memory for characters)
// --------------------------------
// 4000   H
// 4001   e
// 4002   l
// 4003   l
// 4004   o
// 4005   \0
// â¡ï¸ Much safer and flexible than raw arrays.

// âœ… Summary of Differences in Memory

// int arr[] â†’ raw numbers, no terminator.

// char arr[] â†’ raw characters, no terminator unless you add.

// char arr[] = "Hello" â†’ C-style string (null-terminated).

// std::string â†’ object that manages memory dynamically with many extra features.